Behavioural Data Analysis: Instance Complexity (ICexpost)

J. Pablo Franco, Nitin Yadav, Peter Bossaerts, Carsten Murawski

17 July, 2020

This document contains code used to do the behavioural data analysis related to Instance Complexity.

Important note on terminology:

  1. What we refer to as Instance Complexity (IC) in the main manuscript is sometimes referred to as ICexpost in this document.

  2. What we refer to in the main manuscript as Typical-case Complexity (TCC) is referred to here in relation to its proximity to the phase transition (phaseT):

    • In the phase transition refers to high TCC and Out of the phase transition refers to low TCC.

#' Create the formatted table for statistical model export
#' 
#' @param model model to be exported
#' @param title Caption shown aththe top of the table
#' @param outputType "html" or "latex"
#' @param outputName The name of the output file
#'
#' @return The text of the table
#' @export table Exports tables if outputType==Latex
modelTableStyle = function(model,title,outputType,outputName){
  print(outputName)
  # Stores the model in the list with all the models
  allModels_ICexpost[[outputName]]<<-model
  if (outputType=="html"){
      table = stargazer(model, type=outputType, report=('vc*sp'),#(('vc*p'))
                        column.labels=c("Random Intercept"), dep.var.caption = title, 
                        dep.var.labels.include = TRUE,model.names=FALSE, 
                        align=TRUE, column.sep.width = "5000pt") 
  } else if (outputType=="latex"){
          table = stargazer(model, type=outputType, report=('vc*sp'),
                            column.labels=c("Random Intercept"), dep.var.caption = title, 
                            dep.var.labels.include = TRUE,model.names=FALSE, align=TRUE, 
                            column.sep.width = "0pt", 
                            out = paste0("Output/Tables/",outputName,".tex"),table.placement="H")  
  }
  #return(table)
}

plotExport2 = function(plot,outputName, height=3, width=4, units="in", type = "pdf"){
  path = "/Output/Figures/"
  ggsave(paste0(folder_code,path,outputName,".",type),
         plo,height=height,width=width,units = units) 
}

\(IC_{expost}\) and human decision-making

We explored the relationship between \(IC_{expost}\) and human performance in the Knapsack Decision Problem. We found a positive relationship between this measure of constrainedness and human accuracy. However, this relationship was not linear. We found the following polynomial relationship between \(IC_{expost}\) and average human accuracy: \[ Accuracy = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times IC_{expost}^{0.001} \]

dat = mean_accuracy_clean

dat$x = dat$ICexpost
dat$x_05 = dat$ICexpost^0.5
dat$x_01 = dat$ICexpost^0.1
dat$lnx = log(dat$ICexpost+1)
dat$logx = log10(dat$ICexpost+1)
dat$x_005 = dat$ICexpost^0.05
dat$x_001 = dat$ICexpost^0.01
dat$x_0005 = dat$ICexpost^0.005


get_model_info = function(mod){
      model_info = tibble(R2 = performance::r2(mod)[1]$R2, 
                              AIC = AIC(mod), 
                              model = deparse(formula(mod))) 
  return(model_info)
}


models <- list(lm(accuracy ~ x, data = dat), 
               lm(accuracy ~ x_05, data = dat),
               lm(accuracy ~ x_01, data = dat),
               lm(accuracy ~ x_005, data = dat),
               lm(accuracy ~ x_001, data = dat),
               lm(accuracy ~ lnx, data = dat),
               lm(accuracy ~ logx, data = dat))

allModels_ICexpost[['ICexpost3']]=models

results = purrr::map_dfr(models,get_model_info)
results
#print(summary(models[[5]]))
as_tibble(parameters::parameters(models[[5]]))
